_ok : List Tp -> Tp -> Prop` by `support_ok Γ (# s) := ∃ B ∈ Γ, occurs_atom s B`, `support_ok Γ (B ⧹ C) := Γ ≠ [] ∧ support_ok ([B] ++ Γ) C`, and `support_ok Γ (C ⧸ B) := Γ ≠ [] ∧ support_ok (Γ ++ [B]) C`. Prove that every derivable sequent satisfies it: `∀ {Γ : List Tp} {A : Tp}, (Γ ⇒ A) -> support_ok Γ A`.', 'statement_prelude_code': 'def support_ok (Γ : List Tp) : Tp → Prop\n  | Tp.atom s => ∃ B ∈ Γ, AutomatedTheoryConstruction.occurs_atom s B\n  | Tp.ldiv B C => Γ ≠ [] ∧ support_ok ([B] ++ Γ) C\n  | Tp.rdiv C B => Γ ≠ [] ∧ support_ok (Γ ++ [B]) C', 'formalized_stmt': '∀ {Γ : List Tp} {A : Tp}, (Γ ⇒ A) → support_ok Γ A', 'prelude_code': "def support_ok (Γ : List Tp) : Tp → Prop\n  | Tp.atom s => ∃ B ∈ Γ, occurs_atom s B\n  | Tp.ldiv B C => Γ ≠ [] ∧ support_ok ([B] ++ Γ) C\n  | Tp.rdiv C B => Γ ≠ [] ∧ support_ok (Γ ++ [B]) C\n\nlemma support_ok_replace\n    {Γ L R Λ : List Tp} {B B' C : Tp}\n    (hocc : ∀ s : String, occurs_atom s B → occurs_atom s B')\n    (h : support_ok (Γ ++ [B] ++ Λ) C) :\n    support_ok (Γ ++ L ++ [B'] ++ R ++ Λ) C := by\n  induction C generalizing Γ L R Λ with\n  | atom s =>\n      rcases h with ⟨X, hX, hXocc⟩\n      simp at hX\n      rcases hX with hX | rfl | hX\n      · refine ⟨X, ?_, hXocc⟩\n        simp [hX]\n      · refine ⟨B', ?_, hocc s hXocc⟩\n        simp\n      · refine ⟨X, ?_, hXocc⟩\n        simp [hX]\n  | ldiv D C ihD ihC =>\n      rcases h with ⟨_, hC⟩\n      constructor\n      · simp\n      · simpa [List.append_assoc] using\n          ihC (Γ := [D] ++ Γ) (L := L) (R := R) (Λ := Λ) (by simpa [List.append_assoc] using hC)\n  | rdiv C D ihC ihD =>\n      rcases h with ⟨_, hC⟩\n      constructor\n      · simp\n      · simpa [List.append_assoc] using\n          ihC (Γ := Γ) (L := L) (R := R) (Λ := Λ ++ [D]) (by simpa [List.append_assoc] using hC)\n\nlemma support_ok_self_singleton (A : Tp) : support_ok [A] A := by\n  induction A with\n  | atom s =>\n      refine ⟨# s, by simp, by simp [occurs_atom]⟩\n  | ldiv B C ihB ihC =>\n      constructor\n      · simp\n      · simpa using\n          (support_ok_replace\n            (Γ := []) (L := [B]) (R := []) (Λ := [])\n            (B := C) (B' := B ⧹ C) (C := C)\n            (fun s hs => by simp [occurs_atom, hs]) ihC)\n  | rdiv C B ihC ihB =>\n      constructor\n      · simp\n      · simpa using\n          (support_ok_replace\n            (Γ := []) (L := []) (R := [B]) (Λ := [])\n            (B := C) (B' := C ⧸ B) (C := C)\n            (fun s hs => by simp [occurs_atom, hs]) ihC)", 'prover_statement_result': 'ok', 'prover_attempts_used': 1, 'priority_refresh_ran': True, 'priority_refresh_error': '', 'expand_candidates': [{'statement': 'Prove a mixed-handed boundary theorem for the recursive support invariant: if every formula in Γ lies entirely in the left-only fragment or entirely in the right-only fragment, then for every atom s, support_ok Γ (# s) is equivalent to the naive support condition ∃ B ∈ Γ, occurs_atom s B; moreover, any failure of this flat condition in the full calculus requires genuinely mixed-handed context formulas.', 'rationale': 'The solved theorem shows that recursive support is the right global invariant, while earlier counterexamples showed flat support containment is false in general. Isolating the exact regime where recursion collapses back to ordinary antecedent support would turn that contrast into a reusable separability criterion rather than another local lemma.'}, {'statement': 'Define the least context-succedent closure generated by singleton self-support and the three sequent rules, and prove that it coincides with support_ok.', 'rationale': 'The proof logs expose support_ok as a rule-stable invariant transported through right introductions and a single replacement principle for left rules. Recasting that as an exact inductive closure would upgrade the solved necessity theorem into a proof-object level characterization, directly serving the agenda of turning recursive descriptions into durable metatheory.'}, {'statement': 'Prove fragment-wise conservativity of the recursive support invariant under the existing embeddings: the translated left-only and right-only calculi satisfy exactly the translated support_ok predicate inherited from the full calculus, with no extra support phenomena introduced by translation.', 'rationale': 'The repository already has systematic left-only and right-only embeddings, and the solved theorem is global enough to propagate through them. Making that transfer exact would connect the new support invariant to the asymmetric fragment interface already present in the theory and would clarify how support control behaves across the fragment-comparison program.'}], 'stored_expand_rows': [{'id': 'op_000035', 'stmt': 'Prove a mixed-handed boundary theorem for the recursive support invariant: if every formula in Γ lies entirely in the left-only fragment or entirely in the right-only fragment, then for every atom s, support_ok Γ (# s) is equivalent to the naive support condition ∃ B ∈ Γ, occurs_atom s B; moreover, any failure of this flat condition in the full calculus requires genuinely mixed-handed context formulas.', 'src': 'expand', 'mode': 'expand_candidate', 'summary_delta': 'The solved theorem shows that recursive support is the right global invariant, while earlier counterexamples showed flat support containment is false in general. Isolating the exact regime where recursion collapses back to ordinary antecedent support would turn that contrast into a reusable separability criterion rather than another local lemma.', 'source_kind': 'expand_candidate', 'generated_from_source_id': 'op_000032', 'generated_from_source_kind': 'open_problem', 'priority': 'unknown', 'priority_rationale': '', 'failure_count': 0, 'parent_problem_ids': []}, {'id': 'op_000036', 'stmt': 'Define the least context-succedent closure generated by singleton self-support and the three sequent rules, and prove that it coincides with support_ok.', 'src': 'expand', 'mode': 'expand_candidate